item.title: UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson and wife had been living separately for years
item.description: ​UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson's wife confirmed that there were threats delivered to her husband. But they had been living in separate homes less than a mile from each other in Maple Grove, Minnesota, though it's not known when they split. Thompson's wife is a physical therapist at a clinic in Minneapolis and in her work bio there is no mention of her husband.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: ‘Muhammad’ is the most popular boys' name in England and Wales
item.description: Muhammad topped the baby boy names list in England and Wales for the first time in 2023, surpassing Noah. Olivia remained the most popular girl's name. Pop culture, including "Barbenheimer" and musical artists, influenced name choices, while royal names declined. New entries to the top 100 include Hazel, Lilah, and Jax.
item.dc:creator: Naomi Canton

item.title: UHC CEO killer may have used a modern version of rare WWII spy gun: Report
item.description: Former NYPD inspector Paul Mauro said the killer of the UnitedHealthcare CEO does not look like a hitman because he used a very rare gun and had to fire multiple shots to kill Brian Thompson but that does not indicate that he was not a hired murderer. The gun looks like a type that has to be racked after each shot in order to shoot again making it a very rare one.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Strong earthquake strikes US' California, tsunami alert issued
item.description: A magnitude 7+ earthquake struck off the Northern California coast near Ferndale on Thursday morning, triggering a tsunami warning. Minor aftershocks followed. BART suspended transbay service, and coastal areas received urgent tsunami evacuation alerts. While over 1.3 million people likely felt the quake, a USGS yellow alert suggests minimal damage, and no casualties or property damage have been reported yet.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Elon Musk's 4-year-old son X spotted at Senate. The reason is...
item.description: Ahead of Musk and Vivek Ramaswamy's meeting with the Senate and House Republicans Thursday, Elon Musk met incoming Senate Majority Leader John Thune. ​“I think we just need to make sure we spend the public’s money well," Elon Musk said as he came out of the meeting holding the hand of his four-year-old whom he took to the Senate.

Poland gets $4 billion US loan for defence purchases, minister says
item.description: Poland secured a $4 billion loan from the US foreign military financing program to bolster its armed forces. This adds to over $11 billion in US support for Polish armament programs, including Patriot and Apache systems. Driven by the war in Ukraine, Poland's 2024 defense spending will reach 4.1% of GDP, rising to 4.7% in 2025.

item.title: Killer of UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson seen grinning in new photos
item.description: The NYPD released photos gunman who fatally shot UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson outside a Midtown Hilton. The photos, taken from a youth hostel, show the killer's face for the first time. No person has yet been nabbed in connection with the killing though bizarre clues have been found. The shell casings had words 'deny', 'defend', 'depose' written on them.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Work-life balance isn't working for women. Why?
item.description: Working women are experiencing record levels of stress due to competing work and family demands, a new Gallup report reveals. Many are declining promotions or considering leaving their jobs due to childcare issues, exacerbated by high costs and lack of support. However, employers can improve well-being and retain talent by prioritizing work-life balance and providing support systems.

item.title: Bangladesh to drop Sheikh Mujibur Rahman’s image from currency notes amid political overhaul: Report
item.description: Following the ouster of Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, Bangladesh is redesigning its currency. The image of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, Hasina's father and the nation's founding leader, will be replaced with symbols of the July uprising that led to Hasina's removal. This move is part of a broader reshaping of national identity under the interim government.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Who is 35-year-old Ahn Gwi-ryeong who grabbed soldier's gun after South Korea martial law order?
item.description: As many social media posts praised Ahen Gwi-ryeong's bravery, one particular claimed that she is a descendant of Ahn Juhn-geun who assassinated Ito Hirobumi in 1909. "The spokesperson of Democratic Party bravely confronting martial law forces fully armed with firearms. She’s Ahn Gwi-ryeong and descended from Ahn Jung-geun who assassinated Ito Hirobumi at Harbin 1909. Protecting the country against tyranny is her family occupation," the post said.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Anatomy of a Murder: The chilling assassination of UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson
item.description: The targeted killing of UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson has gripped the nation, highlighting tensions surrounding the US healthcare system. The assailant, clad in tactical gear, executed the attack near a hotel before fleeing on an e-bike. Evidence suggests a grievance-driven motive, with cryptic messages like "delay" and "depose" etched on shell casings, possibly referencing denied insurance claims. Thompson’s role in a criticized for-profit healthcare system and the industry's alleged abuses have sparked polarized reactions. Public discourse reflects anger over systemic inequities, raising broader questions about corporate accountability, healthcare reform, and the potential normalization of violence in addressing societal grievances.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Trump's America? University of Michigan drops DEI hiring
item.description: The university’s relationship with DEI initiatives has been both longstanding and complex. In 2016, the institution launched DEI 1.0, its inaugural five-year strategic plan designed to weave principles of diversity, equity, and inclusion into the fabric of campus life. This initiative sought to create a more inclusive environment and address systemic inequities. Following a period of review, the university introduced DEI 2.0 in October 2023, emphasizing goals such as affordability, access, and a renewed commitment to fostering an inclusive community. This broader framework remains firmly in place, even as the university reevaluates specific policies like the DEI statement requirement.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Democrat Ro Khanna says he wants to work with Musk, Vivek Ramaswamy's DOGE, Elon reacts
item.description: Congressman Ro Khanna offered to collaborate with Elon Musk and Vivek Ramaswamy's Department of Government Efficiency to reduce government waste. The statement came as Musk and Ramaswamy are scheduled to visit Capitol Hill today to meet with Republican lawmakers in both chambers of Congress to discuss what DOGE is set out to achieve.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: France PM Michel Barnier resigns after no confidence motion, to stay in office till new government named
item.description: French Prime Minister Michel Barnier resigned after a historic no-confidence vote ousted his government. This marks the first successful such vote since 1962. President Macron faces pressure to quickly appoint a successor amid a hung parliament and political instability. Barnier's controversial budget proposal triggered the crisis, leaving France without an approved budget.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Poetic Justice': Why some Americans are celebrating UnitedHealthcare CEO’s murder
item.description: The shocking murder of UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson has sparked polarised reactions, highlighting the deep frustration many Americans feel toward the US healthcare system. Thompson’s leadership symbolised a profit-driven industry criticised for denying care and financial exploitation. Social media flooded with dark humour and anger, with some viewing his death as karmic justice. Journalist Taylor Lorenz's meme further fuelled controversy, reflecting the public’s disdain for systemic inequities. While critics warn against normalising violence, the incident underscores a growing demand for universal healthcare and reform. Thompson’s death serves as a grim symbol of a healthcare system many believe is irreparably broken.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Does Donald Trump have an IQ of 73? What is the truth behind this viral claim?
item.description: How much is Donald Trump's IQ? The answer is not known as he never released his IQ score though he took jibes at Joe Biden and Kamala Harris and all other opponents by calling them low-IQ persons. In 2019, the claim that Donald Trump's IQ is 73 went viral. The same clip resurfaced on X Thursday making the same claim. An IQ of 73 indicated mental retardation.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: China sanctions 13 US military firms over Taiwan arms sales​​
item.description: China imposed sanctions on 13 US military companies and six executives following US arms sales to Taiwan and President Lai Ching-te's US transit. Beijing views the $385 million arms deal, including F-16 support, as a threat to its sovereignty and opposes Taiwan's leader's foreign interactions, considering Taiwan its territory.
